Roadmap

This file reports simulation results for point estimates and coverage rate constructed with the following different methods:
1. PanelMatch with weights supplied by synthetic control
2. PanelMatch with weights supplied by Mahalanobis distance matching
3. PanelMatch with weights supplied by propensity score weighting
4. OLS regression including lagged DV as well as two-way FE as a benchmark

Simulation Set-up:

The primary DGP is the following.
We first draw two-way fixed effects prior to simulations:
\(\alpha_{i} \sim Normal(\mu = 10, \sigma^{2} = 6)\)
\(\gamma_{t} \sim Normal(\mu = 10, \sigma^{2} = 6)\)
Then, we generate the data using the apriori fixed effects for each simulation:
\(Y_{i,t} = \rho_{1}Y_{i, t-1} + \delta_{1}*X_{1i,t} + \omega_{1}*X_{2i,t} + \beta T_{it} + \tau_{1}*T_{i, t-1} + \alpha_{i} + \gamma_{t} + \epsilon_{it}\)
\(T_{it} \sim Bernoulli(1 - \frac{P_{it}}{1.3})\)
\(logit(P_{it}) = \rho_{2}*Y_{i, t-1} + \delta_{2}* X_{1it} + \omega_{2}*X_{2i,t} + \tau_{2}*T_{i, t-1} + \alpha_{i} + \gamma_{t}\)
\(X_{1it} = .75* X_{1i,t-1} + 0*\alpha_{i} + 0*\gamma_{t} + z_{it}\) \(\epsilon_{it} = \phi_{e} * \epsilon_{i, t-1} + u_{it}\)
\(\epsilon_{i,t = 1} \sim Normal(\mu = 0, \sigma^{2} = 6)\)
\(u_{it} \sim Normal(\mu = 0, \sigma^{2} = unif(3,6))\)
\(z_{it} \sim Normal(\mu = 0.5, \sigma^{2} = 1)\)

The true treatment effect is \(\beta = 1\). We let \(\rho_{1} = \rho_{2} = 0.6\), letting the outcome at \(t-1\) be highly correlated with both outcome at \(t\) and treatment at \(t\). We set \(\delta_{1} = 0.2\) and \(\delta_{2} = 0.4\) so that both outcome and treatment at \(t\) are affected by a continuous covariate, \(X_{1}\), to some extent. \(X_{1}\) is also serially correlated itself but not correlated with the fixed effects. We let \(\omega_{1} = \omega_{2} = 0\), so that another covariate \(X_{2}\) is not going to affect our data generating process at all for either outcome or treatment. We let \(\tau_{1} = \tau_{2} = 0\), so that neither the outcome nor treatment at \(t\) is affected by treatment at \(t-1\).
In other words, this data generating process stipulates that the current outcome is affected by both past outcome and current treatment, and current treatment itself is also affected by past outcome. Both treatment and outcome are also affected by a continuous covariate and two-way fixed effects. Note that we make the error structure both heteroskedastic, by allowing the variance of \(u\) to follow a uniform distribution, and serially corrleated, by setting \(\phi_{e} = 0.5\).
For each simulation, we will compute WFE regression standard errors. We try \(M = 1\) for Mahalanobis matching throughout the simulation, but try both \(L = 6\) and \(L = 4\) for lag length.

Results

We report point estimation bias, RMSE and SD of point estimates for \(N = 50\), \(N = 100\) and \(N = 200\). In terms of finite sample point estimation, our methods recover the truth very well even for \(N = 50\). Note that OLS in this case also performs quite well, indicating that the Nickell bias is likely to be small in our data generating process when \(T = 20\). Nevertheless, our methods still substantially outperform OLS.
Our methods are not as good as OLS when it comes to RMSE, indicating a bias-variance tradeoff. However, note that the RMSE of our methods also goes down as \(N\) grows larger. This bias-variance tradeoff is evidenced in the relatively larger SD of point estimates from our methods as well.
